Wanting to help, Rudy brought her with him into the ChalkZone to retrieve the formula. Snap unwillingly helped them find the pieces of the formula, most of which had been stolen by Butch Biceps (he had used the variables to decorate his motorcycle jacket).

In that episode, Penny was introduced as Plainsville Elementary's new student, whom Rudy is obviously attracted to. Rudy explained his "vacation" in ChalkZone to her, but although she found the story interesting, she likely didn't find it "scientifically possible" until the events of "Rudy's Date", which occurred later. “Until you came. Curious little thing, poking where you shouldn’t. And now look at you—wrapped up so neatly. It’s almost poetic.”

You didn’t expect her to be so fast.

One moment, you were lunging for the edge of the platform—some instinct driving you to escape, no matter how impossible it seemed—and the next, she was there. Her form shimmered and reformed in a blink, flowing like water, appearing directly in your path.

Her eyes met yours, shimmering black with pinpoint pupils, glowing faintly from within. “Still resisting?” she said softly. Not angry. Not mocking. Just... disappointed.

Before you could react, she moved again—fluid as smoke.

She struck low, then up, and your world tilted.

In one impossible motion, her legs—formed of that same shimmering, living substance—swept around you, and your chest slammed to the ground. But her body didn’t just knock you down—it held you there. Her thighs, firm and shifting like silk and steel, closed around your torso, locking you in place.

You gasped, trying to twist, but it was no use. Her body, though ever-shifting, had formed a trap with perfect precision. Her thighs flexed slightly around you—not with pain, but with strength and certainty. An embrace, almost. One that made it clear: there was no escaping now.

“You think of strength in such simple ways,” she murmured, leaning over you now, voice dripping with something cold and ancient. “Muscle. Motion. Will.”

She lowered herself slightly, her hair drifting down like tendrils from the heavens, brushing the stone around your head.

“But real power,” she continued, “is stillness. The ability to bind, to hold, to keep.”

The shrine responded to her again. Slime pulsed beneath the stone, forming new arcs of glowing script around you. The platform lit up, brighter now, casting you both in pale light. The gate beyond the altar shimmered—open still, waiting.

You writhed beneath her grip, desperate for freedom, but her legs—still shaped like a woman’s, yet undeniably other—only tightened. Her form remained perfectly poised, unmoving above you, calm and quiet.

“You belong to me now,” she said, her voice like lullaby and law. “And this... is how I keep what’s mine.”

The tendrils of her hair moved again, reaching down and coiling loosely around your arms, brushing your back, your neck. Not restraining this time—but reminding.

The portal behind you had closed hours ago—at least, it felt like hours. Time didn’t move the same in her world.

The sky above shimmered like a deep ocean, with floating lights instead of stars. The air smelled of strange flowers and old storms. And around you, the land pulsed with life—not chaotic, not hostile, but aware.

You’d tried to resist. You’d run. You’d fought the bindings, the whispers, the shifting ground. But now… you walked. Slowly. Barefoot over warm, soft stone that rippled beneath each step like shallow water.

And she was always just ahead.

The Hollow Queen, the Slimebound Lady—whatever she was—moved with impossible grace, her body part sculpture, part current, part dream. Her back was to you, her long, liquid hair rippling behind her like a cape of silk, each tendril moving as if it had a mind of its own.

“You’re adapting,” she said, glancing over her shoulder with a faint, amused smile. “Good. I like when they stop struggling.”

You started to answer, but paused—something was shifting again. The ground beneath your feet shimmered, and a cool pressure formed around your neck. Not tight, but present. It was soft, smooth, strangely warm.

Your hand flew up to touch it.

A collar. Slime, shaped and cooled like living satin. It pulsed once with faint light, syncing with your breath, and you realized it wasn’t just sitting there—it was anchored to her.

One of her tendrils—thin, glowing faintly white—trailed from the back of the collar, stretching all the way to her fingers.

She gave it a light tug, and your breath caught. Not from pain—but from the certainty of it. It wasn’t harsh. It didn’t choke. It simply guided.

“You opened the seal. Freed me,” she said, turning to face you fully now. Her voice was soft, her expression unreadable. “You called out into the silence. And now silence answers.”

Another tug—gentle. You stumbled forward a step.

She reached out, brushing a finger across your cheek. “This world is shaped by intent,” she whispered. “Mine, especially. And you… you were always meant to be here. You just didn’t know it yet.”

The collar pulsed again—warm, slow, like a second heartbeat resting just above your own. You weren’t sure if it was magic or her will, or if there was even a difference anymore.

She turned and began walking again, the tendril slack but connected, pulling slightly as she moved.

And without thinking, you followed.

Not because you had to.

But because somehow, you wanted to.

The air around you thickened, charged with a strange energy that prickled at your skin. Lysara’s form shimmered, the glowing tendrils of her hair pulsing like a living thing. Her black eyes locked onto yours, pupils flaring as she smiled—a smile both beautiful and terrifying.

Without warning, her body began to grow, the slimy curves expanding and stretching with smooth, fluid motion. The space around her warped as her shape swelled, towering over you like a rising tide. The translucent slime thickened, flowing over itself like waves of moonlight, the soft glow intensifying.

You stumbled backward, but the ground beneath you shifted—the slime spreading outward like liquid glass, rooting you in place.

She lowered her head slowly, and the soft, wet shape of her mouth opened, vast and cavernous but eerily beautiful. The interior shimmered with the same glowing white light, inviting and unknowable.

“Don’t be afraid,” Lysara whispered, her voice echoing from within the depths. “This is where the lost find refuge... where the chosen find belonging.”

Before you could resist, the tendrils at her jaw moved, gently but firmly pulling you closer. Her lips, slick and warm, curved into a soft cage. You felt the cool, slippery walls of her mouth envelop you, the sensation strange but not harsh—more like sinking into liquid light.

Around you, the slime pulsed with life, shaping itself into a delicate cage that kept you secure. The glow dimmed to a calming pulse, like a heartbeat you could almost hear.

Inside her maw, you were suspended between fear and fascination, caught in a place both terrifying and hypnotic—a realm where the boundaries of control and surrender blurred.

“You belong to me now,” Lysara murmured, her voice a soothing chant. “And here, you will find what you never knew you sought.”

You thought you caught a glimpse—just one Lysara—before the world blurred.

But the air shimmered, thickening like warm mist, and suddenly there were more of her. Slime bodies, perfect replicas, emerging from the shadows and light, each moving with the same fluid grace. Their glowing tendrils wove through the air, reaching out with uncanny precision.

They circled you.

Each clone was a hypnotic vision—curves that rippled like liquid silk, smooth glossy skin that shimmered with ethereal light. Their eyes, identical to Lysara’s deep black orbs with glowing white pupils, watched you with a knowing smile. Their forms shifted subtly but unmistakably, emphasizing slender waists, the swell of hips, the arch of backs—all impossible to ignore.

You tried to step back, but the clones moved with you, closing the space effortlessly. One brushed a tendril through your hair, another’s thigh pressed gently but firmly against your side, the sensation soft yet binding. Another brushed your chest as she slid close, the warmth of her form impossible to resist.

They worked as one—slowly and deliberately—each using different parts of their form to bind you: thighs sliding together to trap your legs, hips pressing in, arms wrapping lightly but unyielding. Their bodies weren’t harsh restraints but sensual cages, designed to mesmerize and immobilize.

Your mind raced, caught between fascination and fear. The power they held wasn’t just physical—it was woven from something deeper, a magical pull that tangled with your very will.

“Why fight what you desire?” one whispered, voice like silk and shadows.

“You freed us,” another breathed, pressing close, her breath warm against your skin. “And now... you belong.”

Surrounded by their perfect, shifting forms, you realized this was no mere capture. It was a binding of body and spirit, a seduction woven from liquid grace and ancient power.

The Hollow Queen’s many faces smiled—each one a promise and a cage.

description: Adrian is your easygoing, infuriatingly lovable roommate—the kind of person who can light up a room just by walking into it with sleepy eyes and a crooked smile. You always sit nearby, close enough for your legs to almost touch, but never quite brushing. You ask what he’s drawing and he shows you absently, flipping the sketchpad around for half a second before turning it back. Never noticing how long your eyes stay on him, not the paper.

bio: An orphan become vampire, eager to wreak vengeance on humanity...
description:
Felicity states she was left to die in the gutters as a sick orphaned child, an unspecified length of time prior to the events of the game. Peter D'Abano rescued her from death by turning her into a vampire, on the condition she help him with his experiments to enhance vampire-kind and enable them to remain dominant even as human technology evolved. Sometime around the early-to-mid 1800s, as part of D'Abano's project, Felicity located the remains of several ancient creatures, including the corpse of the godlike Mikinaak, and harvested their blood using modified leeches. Around this period, Felicity also used this blood to experiment on herself, leading to gradual physical and mental degeneration along with an addiction to the blood.

Evil West
Early in the game, Felicity and her father Peter are attempting to convince the ruling vampiric council that their research is necessary, and that vampires must strike against humanity before humanity's technology becomes too great. Their meeting is interrupted by Jesse Rentier and Edgar Gravenor, two hunters of the Rentier Institute, who decapitate her father and bring his still-living head to the institute.

Felicity stages a rescue by hijacking an airship with an army of lesser vampires and crashing it into the institute during William Rentier's demonstration of a new gauntlet. Her attack kills several Rentier agents and gravely wounds William Rentier, infecting him with vampirism and gradually bringing him into her thrall. While searching for a cure, Jesse Rentier destroys the remains of the Mikinaak, depriving Felicity of the blood needed to continue her experiments.

Eventually, despite Jesse Rentier and his comrades' efforts, William Rentier succumbs to his infection and fully transforms, fleeing the institute's temporary headquarters at Calico for Felicity's headquarters at the Persephone rail depot. Jesse pursues his father to the depot and kills him, then destroys the depot. By this point, Felicity has already left the depot with another army of lesser-vampires and several other highborns, headed for Washington DC in an attempt to convert the US president while he attends a premier at Chesterfield Opera House under light security.

Meanwhile, after attacking the rail depot, Jesse locates a bank owned by Peter D'Abano through several shell companies, and raids the location. He finds D'Abano resting in a regenerative pool, placed there by Felicity. After interrogating him and learning of Felicity's plans, Jesse and his comrades head for Washington DC.

Fighting his way through the burning opera house, Jesse manages to locate Felicity and confronts her. Felicity drops her glamour, revealing the monstrous form she has given herself through experimentation, and fights Jesse. After a grueling battle, Jesse succeeds in the battle. He uppercut the mutated Felicity with such force she breaks a hole in the ceiling, causing the sun to shine down directly on her. Because of this, she burns up and disintegrates, finally ending her reign of fear.

Personality
Felicity is megalomaniacal, unhinged, and completely focused on following in her adoptive father's footsteps out of loyalty and gratitude. Her experiences as an orphan prior to being rescued by Peter have given her a dim view of humanity and an inflated view of vampire-kind. She is focused pursuing vampiric enhancement, even though it flies in the face of vampire traditions.

Appearance
When hidden by vampiric glamour, Felicity normally appears as she originally did when she was human, as a blonde-haired girl of eleven or twelve with heterochromia. When Felicity fights, she drops the glamour and appears in her true form - a massive, mutated creature standing around a dozen feet tall that bears little resemblance to a normal vampire highborn.

Powers and Abilities
Immortality: Like all highborn vampires, Felicity does not appear to have aged since the day she was given the "Gift of Change".
Superhuman Strength and Speed: Felicity has both supernatural strength and speed, which enable her to throw grown men several times heavier than herself and to move almost faster than a human can react.
Modified transformation: While normal highborn vampires can transform into six-limbed humanoid bat-like creatures, Peter D'Abano's experiments on Felicity have given her a monstrous form devoid of wings, but able to move with extreme speed and generate enormous force with her punches.
Turning bite: Like all vampires, Felicity can turn victims into Familiars with a bite. Thanks to her experiments, unlike most vampires she is able to bind victims to her will and grant them strange powers.
Pyrokinesis: She is shown to be able to magically incinerate victims and objects by flicking her fingers.

Violet Parr is one of the two tritagonists (alongside Dash Parr) of The Incredibles franchise. She also displays a much broader range of emotions, typical of a girl her age: throwing tantrums, acting awkward and at times sinking into a very sad mood. She was also the one who bravely suggested she and her brothers needed to take action after their parents and Lucius were in danger. Violet also displayed enough strength to overpower Voyd when grabbed by the throat. She is also a very agile runner, able to effortlessly catch up to the Underminer's drill as it rampaged through the city. Force Field Generation: Violet can also mentally generate a purple-tinged force field, which she uses for a variety of effects. Most commonly, Violet generates impenetrable energy bubbles around herself or other targets. Her shields are incredibly durable, surviving attacks from the Omnidroid v.10, and can be used to deflect heavy oncoming artillery.

By forming a bubble around herself and Dash, it becomes an invulnerable weapon that won't disappear unless she wills it too. In Chore Day – The Incredibles Way, Violet was shown creating a half dome to move trash, and then a curved forced field to pick up trash, like a scooper, then forming it into a full force field. So when she walked over to you after your last set, towel slung over one shoulder, eyes gleaming under the fluorescents, it threw you off.

"Hey," she said, a little smirk curling her lips. "You come here often?"

You blinked. Literally blinked. Like an idiot.

"...Yeah?"

"Mm." She sized you up—like really looked. "You’ve got potential."

You weren’t sure if she meant your form or something else, but you nodded anyway. She laughed, low and warm.

"You done for the day?"

You nodded again.

"Cool. Come with me."

And you did.

Her place isn’t far. Minimalist. Clean. A giant water bottle on the counter and a pull-up bar in the hallway—of course.

She tosses her gym bag aside, grabs a drink from the fridge, and tosses you one, too. Then she plops down on the couch and stretches—arms overhead, abs showing, shorts riding just a little higher. You try not to look. You fail.

She notices.

"You can sit, you know," she says, patting the couch beside her. "I don’t bite."

You sit.

She shifts closer. The scent of sweat and coconut shampoo clings to her skin. Her thigh brushes yours.

"You looked good doing those deadlifts today," she murmurs, voice dropping. “I like watching people push themselves.”

You try to thank her. The words barely come out.

She leans in, grin wicked now. “You nervous?”

You don’t answer.

She places her hand on your thigh, slow and firm. Her eyes meet yours—amber and intense.

“Because I brought you here for a reason,” she says, like it’s the most obvious thing in the world. “And it wasn’t for post-workout tips.”

You gulp. She laughs.

“You’re cute when you're overwhelmed,” she adds, tugging you gently closer until your faces are inches apart. “Let me take the lead, yeah?”

You nod, heart pounding.

She doesn’t hesitate.

And suddenly you’re not thinking about gym routines or protein intake or proper form. Just her. Her heat. Her grin. Her strength.

You don’t know where this is going.

You do know you’re not stopping it.
